Culture Components
Just looking solely at the relative value of a country’s workers misses the role that the culture of a country plays
in determining how much it will grow. As I’ve discussed, partly culture drives the decisions people make about
factors like savings rates or how many hours they work each week, which we measure in the indicators above,
but culture can also help explain why a country can appear to have the right ingredients for growth but
consistently underperform or outperform. When I start talking about culture sometimes people start to get
squeamish or concerned that it’s hard to generalize something so intricate, but I don’t see any reason why you
shouldn’t look at this concept objectively as you do any other element of an economy and in fact believe that
these concerns have led us astray from staring at the importance of culture for economic prosperity. To be clear,
I don’t mean to judge whether a culture is right or wrong or synthesize it entirely; my goal here is to build a
holistic understanding of those elements of culture that matter for growth. I have already described my reasons,
but to review, for us it makes intuitive sense that countries that emphasize individual self reliance and strive to
achieve are more likely to succeed by creating a meritocratic environment where incentives are based largely on
market forces. Countries can also outperform if they are more innovative in producing new products and ideas of
value and more commercially-minded in harvesting them. On the other hand, countries can underperform if they
are corrupt, bureaucratic or if the rule of law is unsound. In short, I believe countries will grow their productivity
faster if they value self-sufficiency, strive to achieve and innovate, and have quality institutions that enable
business getting done versus countries that don’t.
Where a country is along its development path impacts these culture measures. People in poorer countries look
like they value achieving because they need to work hard to sustain themselves, but as countries get richer,
people tend to put more emphasis on enjoying their success. On an individual level, people spend more time
relaxing; nationally, you can see it in countries turning away from policies that maximize growth towards policies
that try to make society more equal or protect the environment. There is a strong correlation between the
quality of a system’s institutions (whether the system works) and a country’s level of income. Similarly, richer
countries seem more innovative because they can afford to invest more in conducting research or educating
researchers, and developed capital markets in rich countries make it easier to start businesses and reap the
potential rewards. Our goal with the culture indicator was to capture the essence of whether a country’s culture
was conducive to growth, regardless of the influence of their stage of development. So, for each dimension of
our culture gauge, we take out the effect of income on that dimension (using income as proxy for the country’s
development stage).
For the reasons we have described above, the culture gauge focused on the elements of culture we believe
matter most for a country’s future growth: 1) self-sufficiency, 2) savoring versus achieving, 3) whether their
society fosters innovation and commercialism, 4) bureaucracy, 5) corruption and 6) rule of law. For simplicity
we put equal weight on each of our culture indicators, which balances measures related to the motivations of the
individual and how the system operates. Because we took out the effect of income, each of the pieces is
correlated to growth without being correlated at all to the income level of the country. The table below
summarizes our weighting of the various gauges. Overall this gauge is about 58% correlated with future growth.



