Savoring Versus Achieving
It makes intuitive sense to us that those who value achievement over savoring the fruits of life will be more
successful in finding ways to work harder and smarter to become more prosperous. Of course achievement
means different things to different people. When I talk about a society that values achievement I imagine one
where its people prioritize professional success, creating thriving businesses and building economic security
versus other goals like protecting the environment or enjoying leisure. What’s more, these societies tend to be
ones where there is a faith that competition is fair and hard work will be rewarded (otherwise it’s less likely for
the people to be motivated).
Like with any other element of a country’s economy and cultural fabric, getting to the essence of what’s true
means triangulating multiple perspectives and comparing that against our intuitions. That’s especially true for a
cultural element like this one. For these reasons, we want to look at both the outcomes and the drivers that we
believe would be consistent with an achievement-oriented society. For these reasons, to build our savoring
versus achieving gauge, we put 50% weight on the evidence we see of a society working hard and 50% on the
kinds of values they expressed in an international values survey. For the first component (the evidence we see of
work ethic in things like hours worked or vacation days), we draw on the broad measure of working hard that we
discussed as part of self sufficiency. For the latter component, the expressed values of society, survey data is
difficult to compare across countries so we triangulated with several different questions that were consistent
with our goal of capturing the desire of people to savor what they have or focus on achieving more. Questions
like, “what should the first priority be for the future of the country,” or “economic growth is more important than
the environment,” get at how people value further success or economic growth vs. other values like the
environment, people having more say in their communities, etc. Questions around whether having a good time is
important or whether the respondent thinks it’s important to be successful are somewhat more direct. Lastly,
questions like “competition is harmful” help us get a sense of people’s attitude toward the type of environment
that encourages people to push to achieve. Below we show how we constructed our indicator of savoring versus
achieving. As with self sufficiency this measure is fairly correlated with a country’s wealth and stage of
development (which we proxy with its income level), with the observed effort more highly correlated than the
expressed values. One we take into account the level of a country’s income, our indicator of savoring versus
achieving is about 40% correlated to growth.


